The logic is clear. The modular approach using export and import is fundamental for maintaining clean, scalable React applications. Utilizing named exports in files like mat.js enables better tree-shaking and ensures imports remain explicit. Does the team prefer named exports over default exports to maintain consistency?

```javascript
/**
 * subset/mat.js
 * Using a named export for the subtract function.
 * Named exports are preferred in large React projects to facilitate 
 * better tree-shaking and more explicit import statements.
 */
export const subtract = (a, b) => {
  return a - b;
};

/**
 * App.js (or main file)
 * Importing the specific named export from the mat.js file 
 * located in the subset directory.
 */
import { subtract } from './subset/mat.js';

// Passing five and three as arguments to evaluate the result.
const result = subtract(5, 3);

// The console will show the returned value of 2.
console.log(result); 
```
